ent Species? -- t39. Christian Paideia and the Politics of Empire in Eunapius’ Vitae Sophistarum -- tList of Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis collection presents innovative research by scholars from across the globe in celebration of Gabriele Boccaccini’s sixtieth birthday and to honor his contribution to the study of early Judaism and Christianity. In harmony with Boccaccini’s determination to promote the study of Second Temple Judaism in its own right, this volume includes studies on various issues raised in early Jewish apocalyptic literature (e.g., 1 Enoch, 2 Baruch, 4 Ezra), the Dead Sea Scrolls, and other early Jewish texts, from Tobit to Ben Sira to Philo and beyond. The volume also provides several investigations on early Christianity in intimate conversation with its Jewish sources, consistent with Boccaccini’s efforts to transcend confessional and disciplinary divisions by situating the origins of Christianity firmly within Second Temple Judaism. Finally, the volume includes essays that look at Jewish-Christian relations in the centuries following the Second Temple period, a harvest of Boccaccini’s labor to rethink the relationship between Judaism and Christianity in light of their shared yet contested heritage.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aApocalyptic literature. 0aChristian literature, Early. 0aHebrew literature. 0aJewish literature. 4aHenoch. 4aJüdisch-Christliches Verhältnis. 4aNeues Testament. 4aZweiter Tempel. 7aRELIGION / Ancient.2bisacsh  aEnoch.  aJewish-Christian relations.  aNew Testament.  aSecond Temple Judaism.1 aArcari, Luca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAssefa, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov